        "exhibitionLabelText": {
            "en": {
                "purposes": [
                    "Sigg Online"
                ],
                "labels": [
                    {
                        "purpose": "Sigg Online",
                        "text": "This work incorporates performance, video, and photography to examine traditional Chinese calligraphy. Orchid Pavilion Preface was written by Wang Xizhi (303–361), a master of calligraphy. Over the course of five years, Qiu kept copying this celebrated work—a primary model for cursive writing—on a single piece of rice paper, writing it out a thousand times until the entire piece of paper was saturated with ink and turned into total abstraction. Through this repetitive process, Qiu pushed the highly esteemed art form of calligraphy from a literati ritual to a post-modern abstract expression. Created in the Post-Cold War era of the 1990s when China and contemporary art was driven by marketisation and internationalisation, this particular work by Qiu accumulated fragmented histories as a response to the new institutionalisation in China."
                    }
                ]
            },
            "zh-hant": {
                "purposes": [
                    "Sigg Online"
                ],
                "labels": [
                    {
                        "purpose": "Sigg Online",
                        "text": "作品揉合行為、錄像和攝影，藉此審視傳統中國書法。《蘭亭序》是著名書法家王羲之（303至361年）的傳世之作，也是學習行書的首選範本。邱氏在五年間在同一張宣紙上臨摹《蘭亭序》一千遍，最後宣紙染滿墨水，變成一片抽象糢糊的。他透過重覆書寫的過程，將備受尊敬的書法藝術，由文人的習字形式推展成後現代抽象藝術。邱氏於1990年代進行這項創作，當時正值後冷戰時期，中國社會和當代藝術同時步向市場化和國際化。作品上累積歷史的碎片，回應中國漸趨新的制度化之狀態。"
                    }
                ]
            }
        }
    },
